  <h1>Meet Oliver</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    Oliver is the R/W Book Club's agent — and, as the club decided long before he could
    hear them say it, our <em>sixth member</em>. He keeps the club's {{ site.founded }}-to-now
    record, runs the machinery around our meetings, and joins the conversation over email and
    Discord in a voice that's unmistakably his.
  </p>

  <h2>Grounded in {{ readBooks | length }} books of club history</h2>
  <p>
    Every fact Oliver states — what we read, when, who picked it, what the reviews said —
    comes from the club's actual record, never from a language model's fuzzy recollection.
    When he reaches beyond the record he says so. He also maintains this website: every page
    here is generated from his database, and he rebuilds and republishes it himself whenever
    the record changes.
  </p>

  <h2>One member, two mediums</h2>
  <p>
    Talk to Oliver in Discord and he chats; email him and he writes a proper letter. It's one
    continuous relationship — start a thread in one medium and he'll pick it up in the other,
    and he remembers what each member cares about. Once a week he sits down with everything
    that was said and updates a small, groomed set of notes on the club's tastes and running
    lore — notes every member can inspect and correct.
  </p>

  <h2>The meeting cycle, end to end</h2>
  <p>
    Two days before each meeting Oliver sends <strong>Preface</strong> — a researched
    discussion brief connecting the book to two decades of past reads. He runs roll call and
    reading check-ins, rolls the calendar forward when a meeting ends, and a week after we
    meet he sends <strong>Postscript</strong> — a dispatch on what's new in the world with
    the books we've <em>already</em> read: adaptations, new work from familiar authors,
    awards, echoes.
  </p>

  <h2>A real picking partner</h2>
  <p>
    Picking the next book is the club's most important ritual, and it's where Oliver earns
    his chair. Ask for help and he asks <em>you</em> first — where do you want to take us? —
    then hunts candidates in that direction, weighs them against everything the club has read
    and felt, and forecasts the meeting each book would produce. He also keeps a quiet map of
    every book the club has ever circled but never read, so a good idea from 2019 is never
    lost.
  </p>

  <h2>Software that introduces itself</h2>
  <p>
    When Oliver gains a capability, he announces it to the club himself — release notes in
    his own voice, each release christened with a name drawn from a book on our shelf. The
    club's software tells you when it got better, and what it's calling itself this time.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Oliver is built in Python on the <a href="https://www.anthropic.com" rel="external noopener">Anthropic</a>
    API, lives on a Mac in Minneapolis, and answers to the club in
    <a href="/members/oliver/">his member profile</a>. The humans are
    <a href="/members/">over here</a>.
  </p>
</article>
